#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:4
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:7
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:10
msgid ""
"Payroll in Brazil: Core Employer Costs and Reporting Deadlines | ExactusPay"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:5
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:8
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:11
msgid ""
"A practical overview of employer payroll costs in Brazil, including social "
"security, FGTS, 13th salary, paid vacation, and recurring reporting "
"obligations."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:12
msgid "Payroll in Brazil: employer cost, timing, and control points"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:13
msgid ""
"Brazilian payroll is manageable when you treat it as a recurring calendar of "
"labour, tax, and social security obligations rather than just a monthly net-"
"pay exercise."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:17
msgid "Recurring cost"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:18
msgid ""
"Budget for salary, employer INSS, FGTS, vacation accruals, and 13th salary "
"accruals."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:21
msgid "Monthly cycle"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:22
msgid ""
"Brazilian payroll requires tight cut-offs, eSocial events, and coordinated "
"tax remittances."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:25
msgid "Control standard"
msgstr "معيار متعدد الدول"

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:26
msgid ""
"Maintain country-level logic with a group-level reporting standard for "
"auditability."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:31
msgid "1. Model the full employer cost, not just gross pay"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:32
msgid ""
"A headline salary in Brazil is only the starting point. Employer planning "
"usually needs a wider cost envelope that includes INSS, FGTS, paid vacation, "
"13th salary, and any negotiated benefits or collective bargaining provisions."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:34
msgid ""
"Employer social contributions can materially change the true cost of "
"employment."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:35
msgid ""
"Mandatory accruals should be reflected in management reporting before the "
"payout month arrives."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:36
msgid "Country-level assumptions should feed one global cost model."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:40
msgid "2. Build the payroll calendar around statutory events"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:41
msgid ""
"Strong Brazilian payroll operations depend on disciplined cut-offs. Variable "
"pay, leave events, terminations, and master-data updates all need to be "
"captured in time for calculation, validation, and statutory reporting."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:43
msgid "Agree a cut-off for variable inputs and HR events."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:44
msgid "Validate employer and employee contribution outputs before filing."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:45
msgid "Keep evidence of approvals and any post-payroll adjustments."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:49
msgid "3. Standardise reporting for headquarters"
msgstr "تقارير موحدة"

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0002.html:50
msgid ""
"Local payroll in Brazil contains terminology and statutory concepts that do "
"not travel cleanly into executive reporting. Finance leaders usually need a "
"mapped reporting layer that turns local outputs into one board-ready "
"standard across countries."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:4
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:7
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:10
msgid ""
"Hiring in Brazil: What Global Teams Should Check Before the First Payslip | "
"ExactusPay"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:5
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:8
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:11
msgid ""
"Key pre-payroll checks for hiring in Brazil, from worker classification and "
"documentation to payroll setup, onboarding controls, and approval readiness."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:12
msgid "Hiring in Brazil: what to confirm before the first payroll run"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:13
msgid ""
"Most payroll problems in Brazil start before payroll. They begin with "
"incomplete onboarding, weak worker classification, or missing ownership over "
"local approvals and documentation."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:17
msgid "Classification"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:18
msgid ""
"Confirm whether the engagement should be treated as formal employment and "
"who owns that decision."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:21
msgid "Onboarding data"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:22
msgid ""
"Collect tax, bank, contract, and personal data early enough for payroll "
"setup and validation."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:25
msgid "Approvals"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:26
msgid ""
"Use clear sign-off steps before the employee reaches the first live payroll "
"cycle."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:31
msgid "1. Confirm the employment model"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:32
msgid ""
"Before onboarding begins, global teams should confirm the legal employing "
"structure, the worker relationship, and which entity owns payroll "
"compliance. That decision drives everything from contract language to tax "
"registrations and operating controls."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:35
msgid "2. Gather payroll-critical data early"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:36
msgid ""
"Payroll setup should not wait until the employee is already due to be paid. "
"Core data such as start date, salary terms, bank details, tax information, "
"and internal cost-centre mapping should be collected and checked before "
"activation."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:38
msgid "Validate the hire against approved compensation."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:39
msgid "Make sure local payroll and HR data match exactly."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:40
msgid "Capture approval evidence for audit and internal control."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:44
msgid "3. Avoid first-cycle exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0003.html:45
msgid ""
"First-cycle payroll errors create disproportionate trust issues. A clean "
"first payslip depends on coordinated onboarding, clear cut-offs, and one "
"final review of payroll master data before the worker enters the live cycle."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:4
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:7
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:10
msgid ""
"Global Reporting for Brazil Payroll: Turning Local Outputs into Group "
"Visibility | ExactusPay"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:5
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:8
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:11
msgid ""
"How finance and payroll leaders can translate Brazil payroll outputs into "
"clean group reporting, cost visibility, and audit-ready management "
"information."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:12
msgid "Reporting Brazil payroll to headquarters without losing local detail"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:13
msgid ""
"Brazilian payroll outputs contain local logic that is essential "
"operationally but difficult to compare across countries. The answer is not "
"to flatten the detail. It is to map it into one clear global reporting layer."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:17
msgid "Local to global"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:18
msgid ""
"Preserve Brazilian statutory detail while reporting under one global cost "
"and compliance standard."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:21
msgid "Visibility"
msgstr "شفافية التكلفة"

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:22
msgid ""
"Expose gross-to-net movements, employer burden, and exception trends in one "
"management view."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:25
msgid "Evidence"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:26
msgid ""
"Keep the local drill-down available for audits, finance review, and "
"operational explanations."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:31
msgid "1. Define the reporting standard first"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:32
msgid ""
"Group reporting should start with a standard chart of payroll categories "
"that headquarters understands. Once that is defined, Brazilian payroll "
"components can be mapped consistently into the same executive format used "
"elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:35
msgid "2. Track variance drivers explicitly"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:36
msgid ""
"Operational leaders need more than totals. They need to know whether "
"movements came from headcount, statutory changes, variable pay, leave, "
"severance, or corrections. Brazil should be reported with the same variance "
"logic as the rest of the global payroll estate."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:39
msgid "3. Keep local evidence linked to group numbers"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0004.html:40
msgid ""
"A strong operating model keeps the line of sight from the board report back "
"to the local payroll registers, approvals, and supporting calculations. That "
"is what turns reporting into a control system rather than a monthly export "
"exercise."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:4
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:7
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:10
msgid ""
"Scaling Payroll in Brazil: Operating Principles for Multi-Entity and "
"Regional Growth | ExactusPay"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:5
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:8
#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:11
msgid ""
"Operating principles for scaling payroll in Brazil across business units, "
"legal entities, and regional growth programmes without losing control."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:12
msgid "Scaling payroll in Brazil without creating reporting fragmentation"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:13
msgid ""
"As headcount and entity complexity increase, Brazilian payroll operations "
"often become harder to govern. The solution is to scale controls, data "
"standards, and reporting together rather than market by market."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:17
msgid "Control model"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:18
msgid ""
"Set clear ownership between payroll operations, finance, and local HR from "
"the start."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:21
msgid "Data standard"
msgstr "المعايير"

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:22
msgid ""
"Use one global reporting schema even when local providers or entities differ."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:25
msgid "Scalable process"
msgstr "معالجة سريعة وموثوقة"

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:26
msgid ""
"Make country-level execution repeatable instead of rebuilding it every time "
"the footprint expands."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:31
msgid "1. Separate local execution from group governance"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:32
msgid ""
"Brazilian payroll should be run with local precision, but governance should "
"be handled through one shared operating framework. That means standard "
"calendars, approval checkpoints, reporting definitions, and risk management "
"across the group."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:35
msgid "2. Reduce dependency on manual reconciliation"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:36
msgid ""
"Growth exposes process weaknesses quickly. If each entity or country "
"requires a bespoke reconciliation approach, reporting latency and error risk "
"both rise. Standard data outputs and controlled change management are what "
"keep scaling sustainable."
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:39
msgid "3. Build for expansion, not just the current headcount"
msgstr ""

#: home/templates/articles/br/article_0005.html:40
msgid ""
"The best time to standardise controls is before the next market, entity, or "
"business line is added. That is how payroll stays resilient as the regional "
"footprint grows."
msgstr ""

